  "summary": "Major Metcalf assists Giles Davis in shoveling snow from the back door of Monkswell Manor. After eating an early breakfast prepared by Molly Davis, the Major continues his morning routine while Mr. Paravicini arrives for a meal, behaving flamboyantly toward Molly. As Giles works to clear paths to the boiler room and the chicken coop, Molly receives a telephone call in the library from Inspector Hoggart.\n\nThe caller informs Molly that Sergeant Trotter is being dispatched to the manor. Despite Molly’s warning that the roads are impassable due to the heavy snow, the Inspector instructs her to follow the Sergeant's directions before abruptly hanging up. A frightened Molly informs Giles of the call, and the couple becomes anxious, speculating that they might be in trouble for minor infractions, such as the improper use of ration coupons or bringing butter from Ireland.\n\nTheir conversation is interrupted by Mrs. Poole, a tenant, who complains about the cold in the living room. Mrs. Poole and Mrs. Poynter begin criticizing the guests, specifically questioning the character of the architect Christopher Raun and the arrival of the \"odd foreigner,\" Mr. Paravicini. Mr. Paravicini enters the room quietly and reveals that he has been eavesdropping on their conversation, noting that he never forgets what he overhears.",
